00:11:57.360 --> 00:11:59.235
But that's subtly different.

00:11:59.235 --> 00:12:01.064
You double every
second position.

00:12:01.064 --> 00:12:02.480
And if you get a
two-digit number,

00:12:02.480 --> 00:12:04.617
you add the digits together
to get the digit root.

00:12:04.617 --> 00:12:06.450
And then once you add
all of those together,

00:12:06.450 --> 00:12:08.030
you get a multiple.

00:12:08.030 --> 00:12:10.390
And most people go about
their daily lives completely

00:12:10.390 --> 00:12:12.514
oblivious that all these
mathematical patterns

00:12:12.514 --> 00:12:13.430
are in the background.

00:12:13.430 --> 00:12:16.580
If we didn't have that
pattern in barcodes,

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:18.331
our modern shopping
centers wouldn't work.

00:12:18.331 --> 00:12:18.830
Right?

00:12:18.830 --> 00:12:21.120
Because when you scan
something at the supermarket,

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:24.270
because the lasers aren't
very accurate-- because lasers

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:28.360
make a lot of
mistakes-- physics.

00:12:28.360 --> 00:12:30.250
But thankfully math
comes to the rescue.

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:30.750
Right?

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:34.570
Because if it scans the barcode
wrong, the pattern won't match.

00:12:34.570 --> 00:12:36.490
And so it knows it's
misscannned the barcode.

00:12:36.490 --> 00:12:37.865
And so it keeps
trying to scan it

00:12:37.865 --> 00:12:39.840
until it gets one where
the pattern matches.

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:42.060
The vast majority of the
time that then means it

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:44.276
scanned it correctly and
it goes onto your bill.

00:12:44.276 --> 00:12:46.650
And people get very emotional
