00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:51.260
And so people don't
know that this pattern

00:12:51.260 --> 00:12:52.676
is hidden in the
background there.

00:12:52.676 --> 00:12:55.200
And the same thing happens
with text messages.

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:58.440
So those of you who
know Reed-Solomon

00:12:58.440 --> 00:12:59.950
and the types of
error and coding

00:12:59.950 --> 00:13:01.660
you can do with text
messages, there's

00:13:01.660 --> 00:13:03.560
a fantastic way to look at what
happens with a text message.

00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:05.840
Because when you're
typing in the text message

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:08.010
and your phone is turning
all the characters

00:13:08.010 --> 00:13:10.250
you're entering into
numbers, it effectively

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:12.780
puts those numbers
into a giant grid.

00:13:12.780 --> 00:13:15.224
It goes through that grid and
puts a mathematical pattern

00:13:15.224 --> 00:13:17.390
into every single row, and
then puts another pattern

00:13:17.390 --> 00:13:18.930
into every single
column, and then

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:22.810
puts a third pattern into
subsections within the grid.

00:13:22.810 --> 00:13:25.170
And if that sounds
vaguely familiar,

00:13:25.170 --> 00:13:29.940
it's because it turns your text
message into a Sudoku puzzle.

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:33.080
And so people have a sense
that if you give them a Soduku

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:35.662
puzzle, even though huge
sections are missing--

00:13:35.662 --> 00:13:37.120
all these numbers
are missing here,

00:13:37.120 --> 00:13:39.170
all these numbers are
missing down here--

00:13:39.170 --> 00:13:41.490
if you know the three
mathematical patterns,

00:13:41.490 --> 00:13:43.520
you can recreate all
those missing digits.

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:47.840
And so people, for fun,
do error correction

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:52.110
