00:28:33.490 --> 00:28:35.700
It looks a little bit like this.

00:28:35.700 --> 00:28:38.235
And so this has two
circuits coming in.

00:28:38.235 --> 00:28:40.360
It's basically exclusive
OR but with an extra block

00:28:40.360 --> 00:28:41.090
on the side.

00:28:41.090 --> 00:28:43.390
This is a delayed circuit
to give this long enough

00:28:43.390 --> 00:28:45.520
to run, you slow
down this signal

00:28:45.520 --> 00:28:47.163
so it doesn't get
there ahead of time.

00:28:47.163 --> 00:28:49.204
So there's a few timing
issues with this circuit,

00:28:49.204 --> 00:28:50.110
but it can be made.

00:28:50.110 --> 00:28:52.530
And a few of you
are thinking, well,

00:28:52.530 --> 00:28:54.620
if you've got this
far, what you really

00:28:54.620 --> 00:28:57.941
want is-- this is
the full adder.

00:28:57.941 --> 00:28:58.440
Yes!

00:28:58.440 --> 00:28:58.939
Right!

00:28:58.939 --> 00:29:01.170
So try not to skip ahead to
the punchline without me.

00:29:01.170 --> 00:29:01.670
All right?

00:29:01.670 --> 00:29:03.280
So this is the full adder.

00:29:03.280 --> 00:29:05.769
So you can do any arithmetic
you want with a full adder,

00:29:05.769 --> 00:29:07.810
because you've got the
two numbers you're adding,

00:29:07.810 --> 00:29:10.224
you've got a carry from
any previous calculation,

00:29:10.224 --> 00:29:12.640
you've got the carry out that
flows on to the next column,

00:29:12.640 --> 00:29:13.730
and you've got the
right out, which

00:29:13.730 --> 00:29:14.855
is the output you're doing.

00:29:14.855 --> 00:29:17.510
And so if you can
make a full adder,

00:29:17.510 --> 00:29:19.780
you're effectively
counting any free inputs

00:29:19.780 --> 00:29:21.347
and getting the two digit out.

00:29:21.347 --> 00:29:23.430
Now unfortunately, at this
point, I worked it out.

00:29:23.430 --> 00:29:26.720
To build one of these would
take about 1,000 dominoes,

00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:28.312
and it would look like that.

00:29:28.312 --> 00:29:30.160
[LAUGHING]

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:35.350
So this is me at the
Manchester University.

00:29:35.350 --> 00:29:36.850
This is the maths
floor-- very flat.

00:29:36.850 --> 00:29:38.058
We managed to sneak in there.

00:29:38.058 --> 00:29:41.130
We have 1,000 dominoes, and
we built a working full adder

00:29:41.130 --> 00:29:42.300
out of dominoes.

00:29:42.300 --> 00:29:44.709
And so again the problem was
slowing down the signals.

00:29:44.709 --> 00:29:46.500
You've got a lot of
synchronization issues.

00:29:46.500 --> 00:29:47.660
But we got to slowing
the right ones

00:29:47.660 --> 00:29:48.210
and sending the other ones.

00:29:48.210 --> 00:29:50.480
Slowly the whole thing
worked really well.

00:29:50.480 --> 00:29:52.660
And then we were like,
well, this is brilliant.

00:29:52.660 --> 00:29:55.550
And some of you know if
you chain these in a row--

00:29:55.550 --> 00:29:59.160
if you have adders in row, you
can add numbers of any size.

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:01.030
So if you had three
of these in a row,

00:30:01.030 --> 00:30:03.770
you could add two
three-digit binary numbers

00:30:03.770 --> 00:30:05.720
and get a four-digit
binary output.

00:30:05.720 --> 00:30:08.892
But that would take
10,000 dominoes,

00:30:08.892 --> 00:30:10.670
and it would look like this.

00:30:10.670 --> 00:30:17.850
So I now own 10,000 dominoes.

00:30:17.850 --> 00:30:20.940
So this took us a whole day.

00:30:20.940 --> 00:30:22.720
It took 10 of us, or 12 people.

00:30:22.720 --> 00:30:24.520
We were rotating in shifts.

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:25.150
Oh my god.

00:30:25.150 --> 00:30:26.581
This is nerve-wracking work.

00:30:26.581 --> 00:30:27.080
Right?

00:30:27.080 --> 00:30:28.760
And so we managed
to build a circuit

00:30:28.760 --> 00:30:30.470
with 10,000
dominoes, which would

00:30:30.470 --> 00:30:33.685
add two three-digit
binary numbers

00:30:33.685 --> 00:30:35.060
and give you a
four-digit output.

00:30:35.060 --> 00:30:37.000
So this is a working
computer circuit.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:38.560
This is an actual computer.

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:41.700
I mean, the display
resolution is terrible.

00:30:41.700 --> 00:30:44.530
But it does actually
work as a computer.

00:30:44.530 --> 00:30:45.860
And we ran it and it worked.

00:30:45.860 --> 00:30:47.150
We were able to add
two three-digit numbers

00:30:47.150 --> 00:30:48.316
and got a four-digit output.

00:30:48.316 --> 00:30:51.030
And we had the museum-- this is
Museum of Science and Industry

00:30:51.030 --> 00:30:52.100
in Manchester.

00:30:52.100 --> 00:30:54.610
Brilliantly-- you can't
see it in this shot--

00:30:54.610 --> 00:30:58.500
we are directly in front of
the rebuild of the first baby

00:30:58.500 --> 00:31:00.780
computer that Alan
Turing worked on.

00:31:00.780 --> 00:31:01.890
So it was behind us.

00:31:01.890 --> 00:31:05.190
I could see the vacuum tubes and
everything of the original baby

00:31:05.190 --> 00:31:05.850
computer.

00:31:05.850 --> 00:31:08.310
And I was allowed once
to have a play on it.

00:31:08.310 --> 00:31:10.660
And it's so cool,
because the memory--

00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:13.370
the input for the memory
is a board of buttons.

00:31:13.370 --> 00:31:16.070
And literally each one
corresponds to a bit.

00:31:16.070 --> 00:31:17.610
And so you enter
the ones you want.

00:31:17.610 --> 00:31:18.630
That ones to be a one.

00:31:18.630 --> 00:31:19.350
That one's a one.

00:31:19.350 --> 00:31:21.240
And so you enter the ones that
you want to switch to ones

00:31:21.240 --> 00:31:21.980
and hit go.

00:31:21.980 --> 00:31:24.000
Nominal piece of kit.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:27.010
And I got to meet
Alan Turing last ever

00:31:27.010 --> 00:31:28.980
student who worked with
him on that machine.

00:31:28.980 --> 00:31:30.992
And so he told me
stories about Turing

00:31:30.992 --> 00:31:33.450
where the operating system that
ran the version after that.

00:31:33.450 --> 00:31:34.460
Absolutely incredible.

00:31:34.460 --> 00:31:36.170
Happy to chat about that.

00:31:36.170 --> 00:31:38.090
Oh, and by the way. "The
Imitation Game" film,

00:31:38.090 --> 00:31:38.831
not that bad.

00:31:38.831 --> 00:31:39.330
Pretty good.

00:31:39.330 --> 00:31:39.830
Pretty good.

00:31:39.830 --> 00:31:41.850
The mass is-- I mean,
it was very brave.

00:31:41.850 --> 00:31:44.490
The first half an hour
is Cumberbatch describing

00:31:44.490 --> 00:31:46.810
how you prove the existence
of uncomputable numbers.

00:31:46.810 --> 00:31:48.891
So I was very impressed.

00:31:48.891 --> 00:31:49.390
It's not.

00:31:49.390 --> 00:31:51.897
He just looks
handsome and smolders.

00:31:51.897 --> 00:31:53.980
But if you want to talk
Turing, see me after this.

00:31:53.980 --> 00:31:55.700
So anyway, so we
got to build this

00:31:55.700 --> 00:31:57.420
in Manchester, which
I was so pleased.

00:31:57.420 --> 00:31:58.940
And we did it on the
first day, and it worked.

00:31:58.940 --> 00:32:00.070
At we had a backup day.

00:32:00.070 --> 00:32:02.010
And we're like, well,
let's not waste this,

00:32:02.010 --> 00:32:04.890
because we could have
two four-digit inputs

00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:06.501
and get a five-digit readout.

00:32:06.501 --> 00:32:07.000
Right?

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:07.920
And we did that.

00:32:07.920 --> 00:32:09.400
But it didn't work.

00:32:09.400 --> 00:32:10.950
Two things went wrong.

00:32:10.950 --> 00:32:13.050
Because we didn't
have any more space

00:32:13.050 --> 00:32:15.290
because we had the same
section of the museum kind of

00:32:15.290 --> 00:32:16.180
sectioned off.

00:32:16.180 --> 00:32:17.810
And we didn't have
anymore dominoes.

00:32:17.810 --> 00:32:19.235
So we had to make it
more dense, and we

00:32:19.235 --> 00:32:20.370
had to make it more efficient.

00:32:20.370 --> 00:32:21.770
So we have to cut
back on the timing,

00:32:21.770 --> 00:32:23.603
and we had to have the
rows closer together.

00:32:23.603 --> 00:32:25.284
And two things went
horribly wrong.

00:32:25.284 --> 00:32:26.200
The first one is here.

00:32:26.200 --> 00:32:27.540
We had cross torque.

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:31.370
We had signal bleed from one
row of dominoes onto another.

00:32:31.370 --> 00:32:34.550
So if you watch, this one
here should not fall over.

00:32:34.550 --> 00:32:35.837
That domino should stay up.

00:32:35.837 --> 00:32:38.170
But if you watch as the other
chain comes through-- here

00:32:38.170 --> 00:32:42.124
it comes-- as the other one
comes through, it-- here it

00:32:42.124 --> 00:32:42.880
comes.

00:32:42.880 --> 00:32:43.758
Here we go.

00:32:43.758 --> 00:32:45.710
Look at that!

00:32:45.710 --> 00:32:51.626
And, in slow motion,
here it comes.

00:32:51.626 --> 00:32:54.000
No!

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.340
So that gave us an extra
output we didn't want.

00:32:56.340 --> 00:32:58.798
So that ran through and tripped
what should have been zero,

00:32:58.798 --> 00:33:00.160
and the answer became a one.

00:33:00.160 --> 00:33:02.420
And the other one was here.

00:33:02.420 --> 00:33:02.920
OK.

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:05.090
So let me should you
what happens right here.

00:33:05.090 --> 00:33:07.000
If you watch that
row of dominoes,

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:10.390
it is going to carry
along to this output here.

00:33:10.390 --> 00:33:14.530
But this one should get their
first and, bam, stop it.

00:33:14.530 --> 00:33:15.170
Right?

00:33:15.170 --> 00:33:16.400
I've been watching a
lot of American football

00:33:16.400 --> 00:33:17.580
while I've been over.

00:33:17.580 --> 00:33:20.390
And so, bam, it
should stop it there.

00:33:20.390 --> 00:33:22.510
So this signal stops.

00:33:22.510 --> 00:33:25.590
It closes this gate before
that signal gets there.

00:33:25.590 --> 00:33:27.340
Unfortunately it didn't work.

00:33:27.340 --> 00:33:29.290
If I show it to
you in slow motion,

00:33:29.290 --> 00:33:31.200
is this one so going
to get there first.

00:33:31.200 --> 00:33:32.779
So going to get there first.

00:33:32.779 --> 00:33:33.320
Look at that.

00:33:33.320 --> 00:33:33.730
Here it is.

00:33:33.730 --> 00:33:34.313
Here it comes.

00:33:34.313 --> 00:33:34.930
Coming in.

00:33:34.930 --> 00:33:38.960
It's going to close
that gate, and-- Ah!

00:33:38.960 --> 00:33:40.600
Two dominoes off.

00:33:40.600 --> 00:33:44.560
But at least it went
wrong in interesting ways.

00:33:44.560 --> 00:33:46.270
If it had just been
bumped by accident

00:33:46.270 --> 00:33:47.770
that would have
been very upsetting,

00:33:47.770 --> 00:33:49.927
but it went wrong
in sightful ways

00:33:49.927 --> 00:33:51.510
as to what happens
in actual circuits.

00:33:51.510 --> 00:33:53.420
Because that was a
synchronization issue.

00:33:53.420 --> 00:33:55.865
So I was so please with
the way that worked out.

00:33:55.865 --> 00:33:57.240
Well, actually
the last project I

00:33:57.240 --> 00:34:00.700
did was a collaborative
project using different museums

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:03.960
around the world, and
we use Google Hangouts.

00:34:03.960 --> 00:34:05.950
We used a live
feature on Hangouts

00:34:05.950 --> 00:34:08.712
to link between different
build sites around the world.

00:34:08.712 --> 00:34:10.170
So I was in
Manchester, and I could

00:34:10.170 --> 00:34:11.570
talk to people who
were working in Finland

00:34:11.570 --> 00:34:12.486
and Canada and the US.

00:34:12.486 --> 00:34:15.199
And the fractal, we're
building a mega menja,

00:34:15.199 --> 00:34:17.901
the one that is at MoMA, Museum
of Science and Industry, here.

00:34:17.901 --> 00:34:19.400
So if you want to
go and look at it,

00:34:19.400 --> 00:34:21.524
it's an amazing fractal
thing they've put together.

00:34:21.524 --> 00:34:24.289
And it was great that
we could use Hangouts.

00:34:24.289 --> 00:34:25.705
People could watch
at home, and we

00:34:25.705 --> 00:34:26.810
could cut between the
different builds sites.

00:34:26.810 --> 00:34:27.489
Absolutely brilliant.

00:34:27.489 --> 00:34:27.800
Anyway.

00:34:27.800 --> 00:34:29.224
The last thing I'm
going to show you,

00:34:29.224 --> 00:34:30.599
and then we'll do
questions, is I

00:34:30.599 --> 00:34:32.590
brought the Christmas
present my mom made me.

00:34:32.590 --> 00:34:33.780
I've got it right here.

00:34:33.780 --> 00:34:36.149
And so I'll bring
up my-- is that my?

00:34:36.149 --> 00:34:36.940
It looks like-- OK.

00:34:36.940 --> 00:34:37.440
Here we go.

00:34:37.440 --> 00:34:39.530
So you should have seen
my giddy face on Christmas

00:34:39.530 --> 00:34:45.889
morning when unwrapped a knitted
scarf made entirely out of ones

00:34:45.889 --> 00:34:47.389
and zeroes.

00:34:47.389 --> 00:34:50.373
I had no idea she was
doing this behind my back.

00:34:50.373 --> 00:34:51.664
And she went and she made this.

00:34:51.664 --> 00:34:52.747
I was like that's amazing.

00:34:52.747 --> 00:34:54.989
And when I saw it
initially, I thought

00:34:54.989 --> 00:34:56.949
they were just random
ones and zeroes.

00:34:56.949 --> 00:34:58.575
And so then I went,
well, hang on.

00:34:58.575 --> 00:34:59.380
Hang on.

00:34:59.380 --> 00:35:02.271
Every single row
starts zero, one, zero.

00:35:02.271 --> 00:35:02.770
Right?

00:35:02.770 --> 00:35:04.210
And so that means
every single row

00:35:04.210 --> 00:35:07.615
is an upper case
letter in Unicode,

00:35:07.615 --> 00:35:10.150
because my mom knits the
way she text messages.

00:35:10.150 --> 00:35:13.000
Right?

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:14.260
Old habits die hard.

00:35:14.260 --> 00:35:15.460
Huh?

00:35:15.460 --> 00:35:16.840
And so I was like,
well, I've got

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:18.010
to look work out what it says.

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:18.890
This is Christmas morning.

00:35:18.890 --> 00:35:19.950
I was like this is brilliant.

00:35:19.950 --> 00:35:21.616
So I got the back of
the wrapping paper.

00:35:21.616 --> 00:35:23.092
I got my pen out.

00:35:23.092 --> 00:35:24.484
What a Christmas morning.

00:35:24.484 --> 00:35:26.900
I get to sit around with the
family and decode my present.

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:27.400
Right?

00:35:27.400 --> 00:35:30.550
And if you actually go
through and work it out-- oh,

00:35:30.550 --> 00:35:34.260
I'm now fluent in binary,
by the way, of course.

00:35:34.260 --> 00:35:36.910
Because when people get me
to sign their book, I can say

00:35:36.910 --> 00:35:40.620
do you want that in normal
characters or in ASCII?

00:35:40.620 --> 00:35:42.682
And so I can do people's
names in binary.

00:35:42.682 --> 00:35:44.140
If you're bored
afterwards, come up

00:35:44.140 --> 00:35:45.660
and I'll put your
name in in binary.

00:35:45.660 --> 00:35:49.150
And I suspect most of you
would then go and fact

00:35:49.150 --> 00:35:50.830
check that very quickly.

00:35:50.830 --> 00:35:52.644
And so anyway I was
able to work it out.

00:35:52.644 --> 00:35:53.810
My mom found a quote for me.

00:35:53.810 --> 00:35:55.310
She found [INAUDIBLE]
for a website.

00:35:55.310 --> 00:35:58.120
So it says, "Maths is fun.

00:35:58.120 --> 00:36:00.650
Keep doing maths."

00:36:00.650 --> 00:36:02.600
Except it doesn't.

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:05.440
When I actually decoded it,
she swapped a one with a zero.

00:36:05.440 --> 00:36:07.790
There's a mistake part way down.

00:36:07.790 --> 00:36:09.700
And so it was right on the end.

00:36:09.700 --> 00:36:15.470
It turned a u into a v. A so it
actually says, "Maths is fvn.

00:36:15.470 --> 00:36:16.338
Keep doing maths."

00:36:16.338 --> 00:36:18.730
I was like, oh, mom.

00:36:18.730 --> 00:36:23.120
I hate to ruin your fvn,
but, you have swapped a one

00:36:23.120 --> 00:36:24.710
with a zero, and
she was very upset.

00:36:24.710 --> 00:36:26.670
Because she is quite
the [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:26.670 --> 00:36:28.560
And I was like,
well, actually mom--

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:30.476
because she wanted to
take it back and fix it.

00:36:30.476 --> 00:36:31.930
She wanted to undo
and replace it.

00:36:31.930 --> 00:36:32.070
I said no, no, no.

00:36:32.070 --> 00:36:33.560
The thing is you don't
have to do that actually,

00:36:33.560 --> 00:36:35.490
because to make the
scarf long enough

00:36:35.490 --> 00:36:37.550
she knit the same
message four times.

00:36:37.550 --> 00:36:39.520
So it repeats, front,
back, front, back.

00:36:39.520 --> 00:36:42.035
And she only made a
mistake in one of those.

00:36:42.035 --> 00:36:44.810
So what is means
is all I have to do

00:36:44.810 --> 00:36:49.127
is calculate the average value
across all four versions,

00:36:49.127 --> 00:36:50.960
and they gives you back
the original message

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:52.120
without the mistake.

00:36:52.120 --> 00:36:54.470
And so today, ladies and
gentlemen of Google, I

00:36:54.470 --> 00:36:59.808
can present to you the world's
first error-correcting scarf.

00:36:59.808 --> 00:37:02.103
[APPLAUSE]

00:37:02.103 --> 00:37:06.220
If you would like
to meet the scarf,

00:37:06.220 --> 00:37:07.550
I will leave it at the front.

00:37:07.550 --> 00:37:09.750
It does also sign autographs.

00:37:09.750 --> 00:37:11.940
You have to hold it
with the pen yourself.

00:37:11.940 --> 00:37:13.040
So you're coming to
get a photo of you

00:37:13.040 --> 00:37:13.990
wearing the scarf, that's fine.

00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:14.530
I will leave that here.

00:37:14.530 --> 00:37:16.970
You can come and check the
code to make sure it all works.

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:19.430
Otherwise, I will be loitering
until I get kicked out

00:37:19.430 --> 00:37:20.380
or people have to
go back to work.

00:37:20.380 --> 00:37:21.755
If you want me to
come and deface

00:37:21.755 --> 00:37:24.120
your book so it
lowers resale value,

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:27.024
I'm more than happy to do that
or answer any other questions.

00:37:27.024 --> 00:37:28.940
If I've mentioned something
and you've missed,

00:37:28.940 --> 00:37:33.060
or you want to copy of all the
circuit diagrams for the domino

00:37:33.060 --> 00:37:34.820
computer are in the book.

00:37:34.820 --> 00:37:37.160
And originally they were like,
I put them in, in my head

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:38.540
and looked at it and went, OK.

