00:38:52.794 --> 00:38:53.460
MATT PARKER: Oh.

00:38:53.460 --> 00:38:54.220
That is a very good question.

00:38:54.220 --> 00:38:55.900
So writing the book
what was the thing

00:38:55.900 --> 00:38:57.740
I learned that was
the most surprising?

00:38:57.740 --> 00:38:59.520
There's a few bits
in there where

00:38:59.520 --> 00:39:02.890
I found new examples
of types of numbers,

00:39:02.890 --> 00:39:05.974
because I've been learning
Python as a hobby.

00:39:05.974 --> 00:39:07.390
So I had to program
at University,

00:39:07.390 --> 00:39:08.140
and I hadn't done it for years.

00:39:08.140 --> 00:39:09.973
There was a few bits
where I ran simulations

00:39:09.973 --> 00:39:11.955
to find ridiculous numbers.

00:39:11.955 --> 00:39:13.830
Some of those were kind
of fun, but I kind of

00:39:13.830 --> 00:39:14.730
knew they would be out there.

00:39:14.730 --> 00:39:16.938
If I ran the code they would
show up sooner or later.

00:39:16.938 --> 00:39:19.312
What I really found amazing
was because the book,

00:39:19.312 --> 00:39:21.270
the conceit is it's about
the fourth dimension.

00:39:21.270 --> 00:39:23.930
There are huge sections
about 4D shapes.

00:39:23.930 --> 00:39:28.030
And in 3D-- I knew this before,
but I've never actually looked

00:39:28.030 --> 00:39:30.389
into it-- in 3D you get
with the platonic solids.

00:39:30.389 --> 00:39:31.930
If you've not come
across these, they

00:39:31.930 --> 00:39:33.305
are very, very
regular 3D shapes.

00:39:33.305 --> 00:39:35.721
All the faces are the same,
all the vertices are the same,

00:39:35.721 --> 00:39:36.560
edges are the same.

00:39:36.560 --> 00:39:38.590
And there's famously
five of them.

00:39:38.590 --> 00:39:42.540
So there's the tetrahedron,
octahedron, cube, icosahedron,

00:39:42.540 --> 00:39:46.150
and dodecahedron, in a
random order I just made up.

00:39:46.150 --> 00:39:49.500
And in 4D there's another one.

00:39:49.500 --> 00:39:53.130
So you get the 4D equivalence
of the fine standard platonic

00:39:53.130 --> 00:39:53.630
solids.

00:39:53.630 --> 00:39:55.890
There's another one that
I call the hyper-diamond.

00:39:55.890 --> 00:39:59.770
It's the 4D equivalent of
a rhombic dodecahedron.

00:39:59.770 --> 00:40:04.110
But it is a platonic solid
in 4D, and it's not in 3D,

00:40:04.110 --> 00:40:05.240
and it's not again in 5D.

00:40:05.240 --> 00:40:06.350
It breaks again in 5D.

00:40:06.350 --> 00:40:08.450
It only works in
four dimensions.

00:40:08.450 --> 00:40:11.755
And so visualizing it-- I try
to find a way to visualize it.

00:40:11.755 --> 00:40:16.020
And in 3D a rhombic
dodecahedron is

00:40:16.020 --> 00:40:19.870
what happens if you get a solid
cube and turn it inside out.

00:40:19.870 --> 00:40:22.931
So if you imagine six
square-based pyramids

00:40:22.931 --> 00:40:24.680
and flipped them all
around the other way,

00:40:24.680 --> 00:40:26.100
you get a rhombic dodecahedron.

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:27.849
The same thing happens
in four dimensions.

00:40:27.849 --> 00:40:31.640
If you get a 4D tessaract--
a 4D cube and-- Oh,

00:40:31.640 --> 00:40:34.530
if anyone's, I don't want to
ruin-- you know spoiler alert--

00:40:34.530 --> 00:40:36.455
"Interstellar" they
mention tesseract.

00:40:36.455 --> 00:40:37.912
I was like, yes.

00:40:37.912 --> 00:40:39.440
Oh, and by the
way, I can confirm,

00:40:39.440 --> 00:40:42.800
the fifth dimension is love.

00:40:42.800 --> 00:40:45.940
And so the same thing happens if
you turn a 4D cube inside out,

00:40:45.940 --> 00:40:47.075
you get the hyper-diamond.

00:40:47.075 --> 00:40:47.950
Absolutely brilliant.

00:40:47.950 --> 00:40:49.408
And then, in case
you're wondering,

00:40:49.408 --> 00:40:51.040
5D is any three-point solids.

00:40:51.040 --> 00:40:53.120
And that's every
dimension above that-- 60,

00:40:53.120 --> 00:40:56.570
70, as long as you go,
you'll only ever always

00:40:56.570 --> 00:41:01.210
get the cube, the tetrahedron,
and the octahedron repeat

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:01.889
all the way up.

00:41:01.889 --> 00:41:03.930
And then the other ones
you never see them again.

00:41:03.930 --> 00:41:05.390
And so there's this
fantastic flare

00:41:05.390 --> 00:41:07.785
up of shapes in kind of three
and four dimensions that

00:41:07.785 --> 00:41:08.660
doesn't happen again.

00:41:08.660 --> 00:41:11.660
I think that was fascinating.

00:41:11.660 --> 00:41:13.210
Further answers will be shorter.

00:41:13.210 --> 00:41:13.710
Yes?

00:41:13.710 --> 00:41:15.168
AUDIENCE: Can you
tell us some more

00:41:15.168 --> 00:41:16.955
about the testing
of the calculator?

00:41:16.955 --> 00:41:19.609
Like did someone accidentally
hit a domino down?

00:41:19.609 --> 00:41:20.400
Did you try it out?

00:41:20.400 --> 00:41:22.090
If something goes wrong, can
you reset the whole thing?

00:41:22.090 --> 00:41:23.220
How long did all that take?

00:41:23.220 --> 00:41:23.460
MATT PARKER: OK.

00:41:23.460 --> 00:41:24.950
So the question
was can you tell us

00:41:24.950 --> 00:41:27.815
more about testing
the domino calculator,

00:41:27.815 --> 00:41:31.280
and could you relive some of
those horrifying experiences?

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:34.930
So to this day the sound of
domino toppling on concrete

00:41:34.930 --> 00:41:37.070
breaks me out in a cold sweat.

00:41:37.070 --> 00:41:39.970
So originally I bought a
box of about 100 domino.

00:41:39.970 --> 00:41:41.905
I'd seen a YouTube video
of someone trying it.

00:41:41.905 --> 00:41:43.030
And they'd kind of cheated.

00:41:43.030 --> 00:41:44.670
They'd taped dominoes together.

00:41:44.670 --> 00:41:47.040
And they were doing
the AND gate, I think.

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:48.770
Well, surely you
can do a half adder.

00:41:48.770 --> 00:41:49.555
So I bought a couple hundred.

00:41:49.555 --> 00:41:50.450
And it kind of worked.

00:41:50.450 --> 00:41:51.575
And then I went, all right.

00:41:51.575 --> 00:41:54.130
And so I bought 2,000.

00:41:54.130 --> 00:41:59.150
And then we had the concrete
floor at the University.

00:41:59.150 --> 00:42:02.661
And we wanted to know first
of all is it reliable enough?

00:42:02.661 --> 00:42:05.160
We were really worried about
if it would be reliable enough.

00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:06.770
And can it be built fast enough?

00:42:06.770 --> 00:42:07.990
Because if we couldn't
actually build that thing

00:42:07.990 --> 00:42:08.990
it wasn't going to work.

00:42:08.990 --> 00:42:11.880
And the big problem was having
the junctions work routinely.

00:42:11.880 --> 00:42:14.040
And a very good
mathematician Sean,

00:42:14.040 --> 00:42:17.430
she came up with-- we called
it the Juncsean, which

00:42:17.430 --> 00:42:20.830
was a reliable way of building
the junction, and it was very,

00:42:20.830 --> 00:42:24.280
very, if you did it exactly the
right way, it works every time.

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:25.280
It was very robust.

00:42:25.280 --> 00:42:27.220
And so we built a
stencil of that.

00:42:27.220 --> 00:42:30.017
And we chalked on
all those junctions

00:42:30.017 --> 00:42:31.350
because we knew they would work.

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:33.601
And then you kind of freestyle
getting between them.

00:42:33.601 --> 00:42:36.100
But we knew as long as we used
those for the uncritical bits

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:37.030
it would work.

00:42:37.030 --> 00:42:39.875
In terms of actually building
it, you'd leave gaps.

00:42:39.875 --> 00:42:41.920
And the rule was,
trust the gaps.

00:42:41.920 --> 00:42:43.400
That was our official rule.

00:42:43.400 --> 00:42:44.904
Well, actually, one
rule we had was,

00:42:44.904 --> 00:42:46.570
if you bumped dominoes
over by accident,

00:42:46.570 --> 00:42:48.360
because occasionally you would
knock them and they'd all go.

00:42:48.360 --> 00:42:49.080
You're like, ah.

00:42:49.080 --> 00:42:51.220
The rule was you then
stand up and walk away.

00:42:51.220 --> 00:42:53.005
Because someone
else will come in,

00:42:53.005 --> 00:42:54.789
someone who's now
emotionally invested,

00:42:54.789 --> 00:42:56.330
because you're now
balancing dominoes

00:42:56.330 --> 00:42:57.540
with a sense of revenge.

00:42:57.540 --> 00:42:58.040
Right?

00:42:58.040 --> 00:43:00.740
And so someone else would then
come in and put them back up

00:43:00.740 --> 00:43:01.630
for you.

00:43:01.630 --> 00:43:03.790
And the rule was trust
the gaps, because we

00:43:03.790 --> 00:43:05.350
knew we were going to
bump them over by accident

00:43:05.350 --> 00:43:06.510
and they were going to run.

00:43:06.510 --> 00:43:08.100
But as long as there was
a gap they would stop.

00:43:08.100 --> 00:43:10.210
And I saw one volunteer,
because I just asked on Twitter,

00:43:10.210 --> 00:43:11.840
hey, people come and
balance dominoes.

00:43:11.840 --> 00:43:14.170
And one got bumped it,
and it started to run.

00:43:14.170 --> 00:43:16.700
And he lunged to
try and stop it.

00:43:16.700 --> 00:43:18.472
And he bumped the
ones after the gap.

00:43:18.472 --> 00:43:20.180
And so then they say
and he was like, oh.

00:43:20.180 --> 00:43:21.054
I was like you idiot.

00:43:21.054 --> 00:43:25.462
And then he realized what he
did and tried to stop those

00:43:25.462 --> 00:43:27.170
and bumped the ones
there, at which point

00:43:27.170 --> 00:43:28.970
we were just wrestling
him away from them.

00:43:28.970 --> 00:43:31.219
And if you watch the video--
I've got a YouTube video.

00:43:31.219 --> 00:43:34.195
It's about half an hour
of me balancing dominoes.

00:43:34.195 --> 00:43:36.070
And I explain the binary
and everything else.

00:43:36.070 --> 00:43:39.090
You can see people walking
around inside-- because we

00:43:39.090 --> 00:43:40.990
had to fill in the gaps
when we were done--

00:43:40.990 --> 00:43:42.530
and we did like a fractal.

00:43:42.530 --> 00:43:43.739
We did every like middle bit.

00:43:43.739 --> 00:43:46.196
And then we went back and did
a little bit and a little bit

00:43:46.196 --> 00:43:48.200
so trying to minimize
the possible damage.

00:43:48.200 --> 00:43:51.519
But to load it we left gaps
where the data would go in,

00:43:51.519 --> 00:43:53.810
and you filled in for one
and left it blank for zeroes.

00:43:53.810 --> 00:43:55.720
And we picked random
numbers at the end,

00:43:55.720 --> 00:43:58.390
and then people had to walk
out into the center of it

00:43:58.390 --> 00:44:00.000
and fill in where the ones were.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:02.530
It was the most hair-raising
thing of my life.

00:44:02.530 --> 00:44:03.930
But in the end it worked.

00:44:03.930 --> 00:44:06.600
We had one spontaneous bit where
we were just standing around

00:44:06.600 --> 00:44:08.800
and suddenly a domino
fell over and a bit ran.

00:44:08.800 --> 00:44:10.300
But we hadn't done
all the gaps yet,

00:44:10.300 --> 00:44:12.395
and so we were able to fix that.

00:44:12.395 --> 00:44:13.270
Very, very stressful.

00:44:13.270 --> 00:44:14.686
If anyone's ever
in the UK and you

00:44:14.686 --> 00:44:17.520
want to borrow 10,000
dominoes, let me know.

00:44:17.520 --> 00:44:19.080
I'm happy to lend them to you.

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:20.925
I bring up a place because I
want to buy them wholesale.

00:44:20.925 --> 00:44:22.790
I ring them up and say I want
to buy dominoes wholesale.

00:44:22.790 --> 00:44:23.645
And they go, oh, no.

00:44:23.645 --> 00:44:25.150
We only send them to shops.

00:44:25.150 --> 00:44:26.441
And I said well, I want 10,000.

00:44:26.441 --> 00:44:28.430
They were like, we'll
work something out.

00:44:28.430 --> 00:44:30.180
And so I got them
delivered to the Museum.

00:44:30.180 --> 00:44:30.888
It was brilliant.

00:44:30.888 --> 00:44:32.460
So now actually
schools use them now.

00:44:32.460 --> 00:44:34.570
So schools can
take them for free

00:44:34.570 --> 00:44:36.594
if they pay transport
from the previous school.

00:44:36.594 --> 00:44:38.260
So they get sent
around between schools,

00:44:38.260 --> 00:44:40.593
and they try and build the
circuits, which is great fun.

00:44:40.593 --> 00:44:43.500
So I will do one more
question, and then I

00:44:43.500 --> 00:44:45.850
